Marion Barry, a prominent figure in D.C. politics for decades, has passed away. Born a sharecropper's son, Barry played a significant role in the Civil Rights movement and served as a leader with the Student Nonviolent Coordinating Committee. During his time in elected office, he implemented programs aimed at reducing poverty and increasing opportunities for working people. Despite a tumultuous life and career, Barry was loved and respected by many Washingtonians. The President and First Lady express their condolences to his family, friends, and constituents.